H.B. 838
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
Apr 8, 2025
SESSION 2025
HOUSE PRINCIPAL CLERK
H D
HOUSE BILL DRH40454-MQa-104
Short Title: DIT Agency Broadband Bill. (Public)
Sponsors: Representative Johnson.
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO MAKE VARIOUS CHANGES RELATED TO BROADBAND LAWS WITH
3 THE DEPARTMENT OF INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5
6 PART I. SATELLITE BROADBAND GRANTS
7 SECTION 1.1. G.S. 143B-1373.2 is repealed.
8 SECTION 1.2. G.S. 143B-1374 is repealed.
9 SECTION 1.3.(a) The Department of Information Technology shall use funds
10 appropriated for the Growing Rural Economies with Access to Technology program for fixed
11 wireless and satellite broadband grants, established in G.S. 143B-1373.2, to award grants to
12 eligible entities to purchase installation materials for satellite internet service and for the
13 provision of satellite internet service for a period of up to one year. Installation materials and
14 internet service must be for the grantee's own use and not for distribution to other parties. The
15 Department shall prioritize grant applicants that operate in one of the 39 counties designated as
16 a disaster area due to Hurricane Helene. The Department may also give priority to grantees that
17 offer emergency services, disaster relief, educational services, or economic development.
18 SECTION 1.3.(b) For the purposes of this section, an eligible entity is one of the
19 following:
20 (1) A State agency.
21 (2) A local government entity.
22 (3) An internet service provider.
23 (4) A nonprofit organization.
24
25 PART II. REPURPOSE BROADBAND FUNDING FOR DISASTER RELIEF FUNDING
26 SECTION 2.1.(a) The Department of Information Technology may provide
27 emergency funding to communications service providers, as that term is defined in Section
28 38.10(j) of S.L. 2021-180, to rebuild, repair, replace, and harden broadband infrastructure
29 damaged by Hurricane Helene, including reimbursement of costs already incurred for rebuilding,
30 repairing, replacing, and hardening broadband infrastructure, provided that all of the following
31 apply:
32 (1) An applicant for funding under this section shall only be permitted to recover
33 costs that are not subject to reimbursement from another source of external
34 funding, including insurance.
*DRH40454-MQa-104*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) The Department may cap reimbursement at a portion of the costs incurred
2 based upon evaluation of considerations such as the number of applications
3 anticipated compared to funds available.
4 (3) Priority shall be given to restoration of broadband service.
5 SECTION 2.1.(b) The Department may use up to fifty million dollars ($50,000,000)
6 of the funds available from the Broadband Make Ready Accelerator appropriation in S.L.
7 2021-180. Funds shall be used in compliance with applicable federal guidelines associated with
8 the use of federal funds. The Department may use its emergency procurement authority provided
9 in 09 NCAC 06B .1302 to procure any goods or services in accordance with this section and shall
10 document the request for funding, the emergency situation or need, the area to be served, and the
11 community's need for the procurement.
12
13 PART III. CHANGES TO THE BROADBAND POLE REPLACEMENT PROGRAM
14 SECTION 3.1. Section 38.10 of S.L. 2021-180 reads as rewritten:
15 "BROADBAND ACCELERATION
16 …
17 "SECTION 38.10.(b) The Broadband Pole Replacement Program (hereinafter "Program")
18 is hereby established for the purpose of speeding and facilitating the deployment of broadband
19 service to individuals, businesses, agricultural operations, and community access points in
20 unserved areas by reimbursing a portion of eligible pole replacement costs incurred by
21 communications service providers. A communications service provider who pays or incurs the
22 costs of removing and replacing an existing pole pole, or placing facilities underground to better
23 protect the critical infrastructure from natural disasters, in connection with a qualified project
24 may apply to the Department for reimbursement in an amount equal to fifty percent (50%) of
25 eligible pole replacement costs paid or incurred by the applicant or ten thousand dollars
26 ($10,000), whichever is less, for each pole replaced.replaced or, in the case of placing facilities
27 underground, fifty percent (50%) of such costs.
28 …
29 "SECTION 38.10.(g) A pole owner shall promptly review a request for access, perform
30 surveys, provide estimates and final invoices, and complete, or require the completion by other
31 attaching entities of, any make-ready work necessary for purposes of offering broadband service
32 in an unserved area. A pole owner shall provide a good-faith estimate for any make-ready costs
33 to the communications service provider within 60 days after receipt of a complete application for
34 access. If requested by the communications service provider, the pole owner shall provide
35 accompanying documentation indicating the basis of all estimated fees or other charges,
36 including, but not limited to, administrative costs, that form the basis of its estimate. A good-faith
37 estimate shall remain valid for 14 days. To accept a good-faith estimate, a communications
38 service provider must provide the pole owner with written acceptance and payment of the
39 good-faith estimate. Make-ready work shall be conditioned upon payment of the good-faith
40 estimate and shall be completed within a reasonable time frame mutually agreed to by the
41 communications service provider and the pole owner. A pole owner may treat multiple requests
42 from a single communications service provider as one application for access when the requests
43 are filed within 90 days of one another. A pole owner may deviate from the time limits specified
44 in this subsection during performance of make-ready work for good and sufficient cause that
45 renders it infeasible to complete make-ready work within the time limits specified in this
46 subsection. Any deviation from the time limits specified in this subsection shall extend for a
47 period no longer than necessary. A communications service provider shall promptly be notified,
48 in writing, of the reason for a deviation and the new completion date estimate. A communications
49 service provider shall provide notice, in writing, to the pole owner no later than 14 days after
50 attaching equipment to a pole in an unserved area. This subsection shall not apply to poles owned
51 by a utility.
