1 "SECTION 38.10.(h) A party subject to a dispute arising under subsection (g) of this section
2 may invoke the dispute procedures authorized in G.S. 62-350 in the same manner as a party
3 seeking resolution of a dispute under G.S. 62-350(c), and the Utilities Commission shall issue a
4 final order resolving the dispute within 120 days of the date the proceedings were initiated;
5 provided, however, the Commission may extend the time for issuance of a final order for good
6 cause and with the agreement of all parties. In such a dispute, the Commission shall apply the
7 provisions of this section notwithstanding any contrary provisions of any existing agreement.
8 This subsection shall not apply to poles owned by a utility.
9 "SECTION 38.10.(i) No later than 60 days after the date funds are appropriated to the
10 Program special fund, and on a quarterly basis thereafter, the Department shall maintain and
11 publish on its website all of the following:
12 (1) The number of applications for reimbursement received, processed, and
13 rejected, including the reasons applications were rejected.
14 (2) The amount of each reimbursement, the total number of reimbursements, and
15 the status of any pending reimbursements.
16 (3) The estimated remaining balance in the Program special fund.
17 "SECTION 38.10.(j) The following definitions apply in this section:
18 …
19 (4) Eligible pole replacement cost. – The actual and reasonable costs paid or
20 incurred by a party after June 1, 2021, to (i) remove and replace a pole,
21 including the amount of any expenditures to remove and dispose of the
22 existing pole, purchase and install a replacement pole, and transfer any
23 existing facilities to the new pole. pole or (ii) place facilities, including lines,
24 conduit, and related equipment, underground to better protect the critical
25 infrastructure from natural disaster. The term includes costs paid or incurred
26 by the party responsible for the costs of a pole replacement to reimburse the
27 party that performs the pole replacement. The term does not include costs that
28 the party incurs initially that have been reimbursed to the party by another
29 party ultimately responsible for the costs.
30 (5) Pole. – Any pole used, wholly or partly, for any wire communications or
31 electric distribution, irrespective of who owns or operates the pole.pole,
32 including poles owned by a utility.
33 (6) Pole owner. – A city or cooperatively organized entity that owns utility poles.
34 (7) Qualified project. – A project undertaken by a communications service
35 provider that is not affiliated with a pole owner seeking to provide or, due to
36 natural disaster or other force majeure event, restore, temporarily or
37 permanently, qualifying internet access service on a retail basis to one or more
38 households, businesses, agricultural operations, or community access points
39 in an unserved or underserved area. The project may be affiliated with a
40 cooperatively organized entity that owns utility poles but shall not be affiliated
41 with a city that owns utility poles. A pole owner whose affiliate seeks
42 reimbursement for a qualified project shall not pass through the costs for
43 which reimbursement is sought to unaffiliated communications service
44 providers and shall schedule and perform all work in a nondiscriminatory
45 fashion.
46 …
47 (9) Unserved area. – An area in which, according to the most recent map of fixed
48 broadband internet access service made available by the Federal
49 Communications Commission, fixed, terrestrial broadband service at speeds
50 of at least 25 megabits per second download and at least 3 megabits per second
51 upload is unavailable at the time the communications service provider
